Introduction

Dataset Description

The datasets analyzed in this project consist of the following information:

  1. 1998-2017 National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS) Data: Data related to the number of background checks completed for requests to apply for the right to have a gun ownership permit in each state, permit renewals, and specific types of gun transactions for each of the 50 U.S. states. This project will specifically focus on background check data regarding only gun-type transactions from 2016.

  2. 2010-2016 U.S. Census Data: Demographic data for each U.S. state census collection efforts regarding population information such as overall density, demographic breakdowns by age, race, gender, income and many other items. This project will specifically focus on the available census demographic data regarding race, gender and population density from 2016.

Dataset Columns and Relationships

NICS Dataset:

'month', 'state', 'permit', 'permit_recheck', 'handgun', 'long_gun', 'other', 'multiple', 'admin', 'prepawn_handgun', 'prepawn_long_gun', 'prepawn_other', 'redemption_handgun', 'redemption_long_gun', 'redemption_other', 'returned_handgun', 'returned_long_gun', 'returned_other', 'rentals_handgun', 'rentals_long_gun', 'private_sale_handgun', 'private_sale_long_gun', 'private_sale_other', 'return_to_seller_handgun', 'return_to_seller_long_gun', 'return_to_seller_other', 'totals'

These columns are significant in that they provide us the number of background checks need to formulate the dependent variable (i.e., number of checks per capita) for analysis of the question and hypothesis highlighted below. This project will use the handgun, long_gun, other, and multiple columns to determine if mutliple demographic factors from the Census dataset affect the number of background investigations initiated throughout the U.S. when gun transactions occur. The permit information will not be used in this project.

Census Dataset: 'Fact', 'Fact Note', 'Alabama', 'Alaska', 'Arizona', 'Arkansas', 'California', 'Colorado', 'Connecticut', 'Delaware', 'Florida', 'Georgia', 'Hawaii', 'Idaho', 'Illinois', 'Indiana', 'Iowa', 'Kansas', 'Kentucky', 'Louisiana', 'Maine', 'Maryland', 'Massachusetts', 'Michigan', 'Minnesota', 'Mississippi', 'Missouri', 'Montana', 'Nebraska', 'Nevada', 'New Hampshire', 'New Jersey', 'New Mexico', 'New York', 'North Carolina', 'North Dakota', 'Ohio', 'Oklahoma', 'Oregon', 'Pennsylvania', 'Rhode Island', 'South Carolina', 'South Dakota', 'Tennessee', 'Texas', 'Utah', 'Vermont', 'Virginia', 'Washington', 'West Virginia', 'Wisconsin', 'Wyoming'

While the columns in this initial dataset are important (they separate the data by state for analysis), it is the data regarding each state that is of more signficance. The data will be transposed to highlight this fact and allow comparisons. The individual rows identify the specific demographics that will be used to compare and contrast any correlation between the number of backgrounds checked conducted in each state for gun transactions and the demographics that could impact whether or not background checks are initiatied. The data will be rearranged to match the NICS data.

Question(s) for Analysis

The overall question this project will address is:

What is the relationship between state demographics (population density, gender, and race) and the rate of firearm background checks per capita in the U.S. during 2016?

Hypotheses

  1. States with higher population densities will have more firearm background check rates per capita.
  2. Gender composition of the population will not have a significant relationship with firearm background check rates.
  3. Racial composition will show an overall weak, or no, association to firearm background check rates.

NICS Data Wrangling Steps

The firearms background check data was retrieved using standard Pandas dataframe reading techniques. Following that, the initial dataset was reviewed through the shape property and head method to determine the overall data being dealt with. This shows us that, before working with 2016 data, there were over 12,000 rows for all years involved. This is in addition to 27 columns containing mostly float types, as is common for fields with "NA" data.

In order to properly clean and analyze only relevant information alongside the census data, a new dataframe of only 2016 information was created. The data was grouped by state, and all numbers summed, to ensure we have proper, annual aggregation to compare to the census data. We have removed the permit and permit_check fields which are unnecessary for this project, as well as could cause confusion on final analysis as different states have different permit requirements that would not be accurately captured.

This leaves us with the following final columns that will be used a the dependent variables of the background check numbers:

  • 'handgun', 'long_gun', 'other', 'multiple', 'prepawn_handgun','prepawn_long_gun', 'prepawn_other', 'redemption_handgun', 'redemption_long_gun', 'redemption_other', 'returned_handgun', 'returned_long_gun', 'returned_other', 'rentals_handgun', 'rentals_long_gun', 'private_sale_handgun', 'private_sale_long_gun', 'private_sale_other', 'return_to_seller_handgun', 'return_to_seller_long_gun', 'return_to_seller_other', 'total_checks'

Census Data Wrangling Steps

Similar to the NICS dataset, the initial census dataset was reviewed through the shape property and head method to determine the overall data being dealt with. To ensure only appropriate data is used & compared for analysis to answer the project questions, the columns and rows were transposed so the census index matches the state indexes of the gun dataset.

Following the transposition, and again to ensure only applicable data is reviewed and merged in following steps, the data was reduced to the following columns:

  • population_2016 for population analysis
  • land_area_sqmi_2010 to be used in connection with the population to determine per capita estimates from the year at issue
  • female_2016_percent to review the gender differences
  • racial percentage breakdown columns to review racial differences

Final Wrangling Steps

To move cleanly into data cleaning and exploratory analysis, the census dataframe was joined to the gun background check dataframe. This step was completed by determining if there were any differences in the indexes between the two tables, which there were as the gun background check data contained Washing DC as well as the 4 U.S. territories. Those items were removed for consistent data and joining, as they are not entirely necessary for the overall purposes of this project, which allowed us to cleanly join together.

Data Cleaning

In[17]:
# Convert string/object values from the census data into consistent numeric values for analysis
def format_to_nums(num):
    try:
        if num is None:
            return None

        num_str = str(num).strip()

        if "%" in num_str:
            num_str = num_str.replace("%", "").replace(",", "")
            return float(num_str)
        elif "," in num_str:
            num_str = num_str.replace(",", "")
            return float(num_str)
        else:
            percentage = float(num_str)
            return percentage * 100
    except:
        return None

Data Cleaning Steps

After merging the background check and census datasets for 2016, multiple census values (which were strings with commas and percent signs) were reformatted into numeric floats and percentages were made proportional (01) to avoid confusion with other numbering in the background check data. Missing Pacific Islander values were imputed with the mean of other available information to remove nulls.

Variables were then created to allow analysis with the dependent variable and complete independent variable items: population density, male percentage (calculated by subtracting 1 from the female percentage), and firearm background checks divided by the population and multipled per 1,000 residents. These steps now ensure all our variables are consistent and comparable across the U.S..

Dependent Variable Analysis

In reviewing the initial distributions for the number of firearms background checks per capita, our dependent variable, the statistical details, histogram and box plots reveal the number of tax checks skews heavily towards the low end. This shows that most states most states perform, on average, 44 background checks per 1,000 residents for gun transaction. While multiple states such as New York showed less than 1 check per 1,000, West Virginia and Alaska perform between 100 and 120. A standard deviation of around 35 implies the highest states do a majority of the 'heavy lifting' for firearms background checks. This creates an interesting data point for review later when comparing to population density and the other factors of gender and race.

Racial Composition Analysis

Racial composition varies widely across U.S. states. White populations make up the majority of residents in all states but range from 26 percent to over 90 percent in some cases. Black populations average only about 11% in 2016 but reach nearly 40% in a few states. The other groups (Asian, American Indian/Alaska Native, Pacific Islander, and Two or More Races) are generally fewer overall with 5 to 10 percent but a few outliers are found in some states.

The boxplot highlights this variability and shows that White populations have the clear highest percentages well above any other group but also have one of the largest spreads with their outliers. Most other groups are slightly above zero with occasional higher outliers. These racial composition proportions give a good contrast for analysis when we examine whether the proporitions of specific groups provide any differences in firearm background check activity.

Question 3 Analysis: Racial Composition

The final analsys of the Correlations between racial composition and firearm background check rates were fairly weak to very weak across the board. Scatter plots were created for each race and only one, the Asian population, showed a potentially weak correlation when values are taken non-linearly with a Spearman correlation. But, linearly, there is no signficant correlation found. All the races are similar in showing no definitive patterns throughout the racial compositions for each state.

The bar chart summarizes Pearson correlations for each group: White (0.2364), Black (0.0867), Asian (0.2544), Pacific Islander (0.1567), and Two or More Races (0.1654) all showed negative associations. American Indian/Alaska Native was the only race to display a positive correlation (+0.0208) but still not significant.

Conclusions

This analysis project investigated the relationship between multiple demographic factors (population density, gender, and race) against FBI firearm background check rates across all U.S. states in 2016.

Population density showed a weak negative correlation (0.33). This is the only potential correlation found and suggests that very dense states, again for example New York, Rhode Island and New Jersey, have lower per-capita background checks compared to their dense populations but the overall association is fairly weak. This indicates that density may have some influence on background check rates but it is not a confident predictor on its own.

Gender composition was nearly identical across states (almost 50% for both males and females). Results showed no meaningful relationship when viewed against firearm background check activity (approximately 0.27 for females and near identical for males in the positive direction). In summary, gender proportions do not explain or provide much information on differences in background check activity across states.

Racial composition varied more widely but still exhibited only weak correlations. White and Black proportions were essentially uncorrelated with check rates, while Asian and Two+ race populations had slightly stronger negative associations. American Indian/Alaska Native populations were the only group with a small positive correlation. This suggests that racial proportions, similar to gender, do not strongly predict there will be variation in firearm background check rates. One group, the Asian population as previously noted, did show the only instance of slightly stronger negative correlation.

Overall, the results indicate that state-level demographic compositions and populations do not strongly predict firearm background check activity. Outlier states like West Virginia (high amount of checks but lower population density) and New York (low amount of checks with higher population density) highlight that policy, culture and other regulatory factors play a larger role than demographics on their own in terms of states completing required firearm transaction background checks.

In terms of hypotheses stated in the intro:

  1. Population density displayed a weak, negative relationship with background check. States with higher population densities did not actually conduct more background checks per capita than states with lower densities.
  2. Gender showed real or significant effect on firearm background checks in either gender's case. This hypothesis was correct based on the analysis conducted.
  3. Racial composition correlations were weak across the board which, again, was the hypothesis put forward.

The final correlation summary bar chart, shown directly above, provides the final results all demographic factors had correlations close to or near near zero, with no variable reaching +/- 0.4.

Limitation Analysis

This project analysis has multiple limitations that must be acknowledged.

  1. In terms of demographics information, or at least the demographics covered in this particular analysis, the dataset is limited to 2016. While there are a few other time periods mentioned for other categories, they are also specific to certain years and snapshots in time. Because of the limited information available for a single year, we cannot capture changes in demographic or firearm background checks over time.

  2. The NICS dataset only records firearm background checks and not firearm purchases. That means the counts may not directly reflect sales behavior which would haved allowed a much more thorough analysis of actual social impacts brought about by differences in race and gender.

  3. The Census data had inconsistencies and errors in multiple pieces of data (e.g., some states reported proportional data instead of percentages which mixed data and required custom functions). There were also a few states with missing values for an entire racial category (Pacific Islanders), which required cleaning and imputation which could affect overall precision.

  4. Lastly, because the analysis is based on state-level data, there could be differences and effects happening with demographics from within-state differences. We are unable to interpret these causal relationships.

These limitations more clearly identify that this analysis provides useful insights into potential correlations between demographics and firearms background checks, but further research with cleaner and more drilled-down data would provide stronger conclusions.
